<paragraph blockId="6.[151,638,971,1072]" pageId="6" pageNumber="712">
Our westernmost record, from Rainy Lake, is west of the Ontario distribution mapped by 
<collectingCountry box="[578,638,1051,1072]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="6" pageNumber="712">Wallis</collectingCountry>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[685,1172,851,1072]" lastBlockId="7.[173,659,858,906]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="713" pageId="6" pageNumber="712">
(1961) 
<materialsCitation collectorName="D. P. Duran" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="713" location="North America" municipality="eastern North America" pageId="6" pageNumber="712" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Ontario">
but within the range mapped by Pearson 
<emphasis box="[685,735,877,899]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="712">et al.</emphasis>
(2015) (
<figureCitation box="[818,876,878,899]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[175,206,1711,1730]" captionTargetBox="[151,1173,1105,1694]" captionTargetId="figure-137@6.[151,1173,1105,1694]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 5. Northern Ontario distribution map showing new and previous collection records for Cicindela hirticollis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378067" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378067/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="712">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Based on the ranges mapped by Pearson 
<emphasis box="[800,850,906,928]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="712">et al.</emphasis>
(2015), northern 
<collectingRegion box="[1022,1094,907,928]" country="Canada" name="Ontario" pageId="6" pageNumber="712">Ontario</collectingRegion>
records belong to the subspecies 
<taxonomicName authority="hirticollis" box="[940,1166,935,957]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Cicindela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="712" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="hirticollis" subSpecies="hirticollis">
<emphasis box="[940,1166,935,957]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="712">C. hirticollis hirticollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, though new research suggests that this species is genetically homogenous in 
<collectingMunicipality box="[953,1171,993,1014]" pageId="6" pageNumber="712">eastern North America</collectingMunicipality>
(
<collectorName box="[693,817,1022,1043]" pageId="6" pageNumber="712">D. P. Duran</collectorName>
, unpublished data). This species is widely distributed across 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:FC3BE42EFFE43A1FFF17FC2CFDF5FC35:714D03E3FFE43A1EFC27FBFCFB8FFB8F" box="[935,1080,1051,1072]" municipality="eastern North America" name="North America" pageId="6" pageNumber="712" stateProvince="Ontario">North America</location>
(Pearson 
<emphasis box="[173,222,858,880]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="713">et al.</emphasis>
2015), and in 
<collectingRegion box="[361,433,859,880]" country="Canada" name="Ontario" pageId="7" pageNumber="713">Ontario</collectingRegion>
it is almost exclusively found on sandy edges of rivers and lakes
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
